const rawHTML = `
<div class="c">

<!-- Hero -->
<div class="hero">
  <div class="hero-k">Comparison &middot; GLP-1 Agonists &middot; Weight Loss</div>
  <h1>Semaglutide vs Tirzepatide: The Ultimate Comparison</h1>
  <p class="sub">Two blockbuster weight loss drugs go head to head. One targets GLP-1 alone; the other hits both GLP-1 and GIP. Here's how they actually compare on weight loss, side effects, cost, and cardiovascular outcomes.</p>
  <div class="pills">
    <span class="pill">GLP-1 &middot; Single Agonist</span>
    <span class="pill">GLP-1 + GIP &middot; Dual Agonist</span>
    <span class="pill">Once-Weekly Injection</span>
    <span class="pill">Weight Loss &middot; Diabetes</span>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Stats -->
<div class="sr">
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c1">~15%</div><div class="l">Semaglutide<br>Avg Weight Loss</div></div>
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c2">~22.5%</div><div class="l">Tirzepatide<br>Avg Weight Loss</div></div>
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c3">20%</div><div class="l">CV Event Reduction<br>(Semaglutide)</div></div>
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c4">1x/wk</div><div class="l">Injection Frequency<br>Both Drugs</div></div>
</div>

<p>The obesity treatment space changed forever with the arrival of <a href="/articles/semaglutide-weight-loss-guide">GLP-1 receptor agonists</a>. First came semaglutide (Ozempic, Wegovy), setting a new benchmark for pharmaceutical weight loss. Then <a href="/articles/tirzepatide-complete-guide">tirzepatide</a> (Mounjaro, Zepbound) arrived and raised the bar even higher.</p>

<p>But which one is actually better for you? The answer depends on your goals, your medical history, and your insurance coverage. This guide breaks down everything you need to know, head to head.</p>

<div class="d">
  <div class="s">What This Guide Covers</div>
  <p>This is an educational comparison of semaglutide and tirzepatide based on published clinical trial data. It is <strong>not a recommendation to use either medication</strong>. Both require a prescription and medical supervision. Consult a qualified healthcare provider before starting any treatment.</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== MECHANISM COMPARISON ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>How They Work: Single vs Dual Agonism</h2>

<p>Both drugs belong to the incretin family, but they take fundamentally different approaches. Semaglutide activates only the GLP-1 receptor. Tirzepatide activates both GLP-1 and GIP receptors simultaneously.</p>

<p>That distinction matters more than you might think. GIP (glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide) adds complementary effects on insulin sensitivity, fat tissue metabolism, and appetite regulation in the brain (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32866435/">Samms et al., 2020</a>).</p>

<div class="svg-box">
  <div class="st">Single Agonism vs Dual Agonism: Mechanism Comparison</div>
  <div class="ss">Semaglutide (GLP-1 only) vs Tirzepatide (GLP-1 + GIP)</div>
  <svg viewBox="0 0 700 300" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
    <!-- Semaglutide side -->
    <rect x="15" y="10" width="320" height="280" rx="12" fill="#E8EEF9" stroke="#2956A6" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="175" y="38" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Lora,serif" font-size="15" font-weight="700" fill="#2956A6">Semaglutide</text>
    <text x="175" y="55" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="9" fill="#2956A6" letter-spacing="1" font-weight="600">SINGLE AGONIST (GLP-1)</text>
    <line x1="35" y1="65" x2="315" y2="65" stroke="#2956A6" stroke-opacity=".2"/>

    <!-- GLP-1 box inside semaglutide -->
    <rect x="35" y="80" width="280" height="90" rx="8" fill="#fff" stroke="#2956A6" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity=".3"/>
    <text x="175" y="100" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#2956A6">GLP-1 Receptor Activation</text>
    <text x="175" y="118" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="10.5" fill="#1E3362">Appetite suppression</text>
    <text x="175" y="134" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="10.5" fill="#1E3362">Slows gastric emptying (strong)</text>
    <text x="175" y="150" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="10.5" fill="#1E3362">Glucose-dependent insulin release</text>

    <!-- No GIP box -->
    <rect x="35" y="185" width="280" height="45" rx="8" fill="#FDEEEC" stroke="#B53A3A" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity=".3"/>
    <text x="175" y="212" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#B53A3A">No GIP Activity</text>

    <!-- Outcome -->
    <text x="175" y="258" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="9" fill="#2956A6" font-weight="600">TYPICAL RESULT</text>
    <text x="175" y="276" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="11" fill="#1E3362" font-weight="500">~15% body weight loss at 68 weeks</text>

    <!-- Tirzepatide side -->
    <rect x="365" y="10" width="320" height="280" rx="12" fill="#E4F5EF" stroke="#187A62" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="525" y="38" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Lora,serif" font-size="15" font-weight="700" fill="#187A62">Tirzepatide</text>
    <text x="525" y="55" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="9" fill="#187A62" letter-spacing="1" font-weight="600">DUAL AGONIST (GLP-1 + GIP)</text>
    <line x1="385" y1="65" x2="665" y2="65" stroke="#187A62" stroke-opacity=".2"/>

    <!-- GLP-1 box inside tirzepatide -->
    <rect x="385" y="80" width="280" height="90" rx="8" fill="#fff" stroke="#187A62" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity=".3"/>
    <text x="525" y="100" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#187A62">GLP-1 Receptor Activation</text>
    <text x="525" y="118" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="10.5" fill="#14503E">Appetite suppression</text>
    <text x="525" y="134" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="10.5" fill="#14503E">Slows gastric emptying (moderate)</text>
    <text x="525" y="150" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="10.5" fill="#14503E">Glucose-dependent insulin release</text>

    <!-- GIP box -->
    <rect x="385" y="185" width="280" height="45" rx="8" fill="#FFF7E5" stroke="#B48118" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity=".3"/>
    <text x="525" y="203" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#B48118">GIP Receptor Activation</text>
    <text x="525" y="220" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="10.5" fill="#5A4010">Insulin sensitivity + fat metabolism + brain appetite control</text>

    <!-- Outcome -->
    <text x="525" y="258" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="9" fill="#187A62" font-weight="600">TYPICAL RESULT</text>
    <text x="525" y="276" text-anchor="middle" font-family="DM Sans,sans-serif" font-size="11" fill="#14503E" font-weight="500">~22.5% body weight loss at 72 weeks</text>
  </svg>
</div>

<h3>Mechanism Breakdown</h3>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Mechanism</th><th>Semaglutide</th><th>Tirzepatide</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>GLP-1 receptor agonism</strong></td><td>Strong</td><td>Strong</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>GIP receptor agonism</strong></td><td class="r">None</td><td class="g">Strong</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Appetite suppression</strong></td><td>Yes</td><td class="g">Yes (stronger)</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Gastric emptying</strong></td><td>Slows significantly</td><td>Slows moderately</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Insulin secretion</strong></td><td>Glucose-dependent</td><td>Glucose-dependent</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Glucagon suppression</strong></td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Energy expenditure</strong></td><td class="y">Minimal effect</td><td class="g">Potentially increased via GIP</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Key Finding</div>
  <p>The dual agonism of tirzepatide appears to produce additive effects beyond <a href="/articles/semaglutide-weight-loss-guide">GLP-1</a> alone. GIP enhances insulin sensitivity, complements appetite regulation in the brain, and directly affects fat tissue metabolism (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32866435/">Samms et al., 2020</a>).</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== WEIGHT LOSS ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Weight Loss Results: Clinical Trial Data</h2>

<p>This is where the numbers get interesting. Both drugs produce meaningful weight loss, but the gap between them is significant and consistent across trials.</p>

<h3>Pivotal Trial Comparison</h3>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Semaglutide 2.4 mg (STEP 1)</th><th>Tirzepatide 15 mg (SURMOUNT-1)</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Duration</strong></td><td>68 weeks</td><td>72 weeks</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Population</strong></td><td>Non-diabetic obese/overweight</td><td>Non-diabetic obese/overweight</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Baseline BMI</strong></td><td>37.8 kg/m&sup2;</td><td>37.4 kg/m&sup2;</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Average weight loss</strong></td><td>~15%</td><td class="g">~22.5%</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>&ge;10% weight loss</strong></td><td>69.1%</td><td class="g">85.5%</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>&ge;15% weight loss</strong></td><td>50.5%</td><td class="g">67.5%</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>&ge;20% weight loss</strong></td><td>32.0%</td><td class="g">50.7%</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Waist circumference</strong></td><td>&ndash;13.5 cm</td><td class="g">&ndash;17.8 cm</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>BP reduction (SBP/DBP)</strong></td><td>&ndash;6.2/&ndash;2.6 mmHg</td><td class="g">&ndash;7.2/&ndash;4.9 mmHg</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Triglyceride reduction</strong></td><td>&ndash;15%</td><td class="g">&ndash;20%</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--mut);">Sources: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33567185/">Wilding et al., 2021</a>; <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35658024/">Jastreboff et al., 2022</a></p>

<h3>Weight Loss by Starting BMI</h3>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Starting BMI</th><th>Semaglutide</th><th>Tirzepatide</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>&lt;30 kg/m&sup2;</strong></td><td>12.4%</td><td class="g">18.9%</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>30&ndash;35 kg/m&sup2;</strong></td><td>14.7%</td><td class="g">22.1%</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>&gt;35 kg/m&sup2;</strong></td><td>15.8%</td><td class="g">23.3%</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>The pattern is clear. Tirzepatide outperforms semaglutide across every BMI category, with the advantage growing slightly at higher starting weights.</p>

<h3>Head-to-Head: SURPASS-2</h3>

<p>The only direct comparison trial pitted semaglutide 1 mg against multiple tirzepatide doses in people with type 2 diabetes (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34170647/">Frias et al., 2021</a>). These are diabetes doses, not the higher obesity doses, but the relative differences are informative.</p>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Semaglutide 1 mg</th><th>Tirzepatide 5 mg</th><th>Tirzepatide 10 mg</th><th>Tirzepatide 15 mg</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>HbA1c reduction</strong></td><td>1.86%</td><td>2.01%</td><td class="g">2.24%</td><td class="g">2.30%</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Weight loss</strong></td><td>5.7 kg</td><td>7.6 kg</td><td class="g">9.3 kg</td><td class="g">11.2 kg</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>HbA1c &lt;7%</strong></td><td>68%</td><td>82%</td><td class="g">86%</td><td class="g">89%</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<div class="d-p">
  <div class="s">Real-World Evidence</div>
  <p>Observational studies confirm the trial data. Tirzepatide users achieve about 5.2% more weight loss on average. Weight loss plateaus around 6 months for both drugs. Notably, 44% of semaglutide non-responders achieve &gt;10% weight loss when switching to tirzepatide (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2024realworld">Singh et al., 2024</a>).</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== CARDIOVASCULAR OUTCOMES ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Cardiovascular Outcomes</h2>

<p>This is where semaglutide has a clear advantage today. The SELECT trial proved that semaglutide reduces major cardiovascular events by 20% in people with obesity and established heart disease (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37788506/">Lincoff et al., 2023</a>). Tirzepatide's cardiovascular outcomes trial (SURPASS-CVOT) is still ongoing.</p>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Outcome</th><th>Semaglutide</th><th>Tirzepatide</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Major CV event reduction</strong></td><td class="g">20% (SELECT trial)</td><td class="y">Ongoing (SURPASS-CVOT)</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Heart failure hospitalizations</strong></td><td class="g">18% reduction</td><td class="y">Data pending</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Blood pressure impact</strong></td><td>Moderate reduction</td><td class="g">Significant reduction</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Lipid improvements</strong></td><td>Modest improvement</td><td class="g">Stronger improvement</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<div class="d-a">
  <div class="s">Important Note</div>
  <p>If you have established cardiovascular disease, semaglutide is the only option with proven CV event reduction. Until tirzepatide's CVOT data is published, semaglutide remains the evidence-based choice for this population (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35665856/">Del Prato et al., 2022</a>).</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== SIDE EFFECTS ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Side Effect Comparison</h2>

<p>GI side effects are the most common reason people discontinue either drug. The good news: tirzepatide tends to cause fewer GI issues despite producing greater weight loss. The bad news: both drugs can make you miserable during the first few weeks of dose escalation.</p>

<h3>Gastrointestinal Side Effects</h3>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Side Effect</th><th>Semaglutide 2.4 mg</th><th>Tirzepatide 15 mg</th><th>Onset</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
