<!-- ========== FAQ ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq">
  <details>
    <summary>Can I switch from semaglutide to tirzepatide?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Yes. The recommended protocol is to stop semaglutide, wait 2&ndash;4 weeks, then start tirzepatide at 2.5 mg. Monitor closely for increased side effects during the transition period. About 44% of semaglutide non-responders achieve meaningful weight loss after switching.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Which drug produces more weight loss?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Tirzepatide produces significantly more weight loss in clinical trials: roughly 22.5% vs 15% for semaglutide at maximum doses over similar timeframes. The advantage holds across all BMI categories and is consistent in both trial and real-world data.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Are there cancer risks with these medications?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Thyroid C-cell tumors have been observed in rodent studies but have never been confirmed in humans. Both drugs are contraindicated in people with a personal or family history of medullary thyroid cancer or MEN2 syndrome. Routine cancer monitoring beyond standard care is not currently recommended.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>What about muscle loss on these drugs?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Both medications cause 25&ndash;40% lean mass loss alongside fat loss. This is a real concern. You can mitigate it with a high-protein diet (1.6&ndash;2.2g/kg daily), resistance training at least 3 times per week, adequate sleep, and proper hydration. Without these measures, you'll lose significant muscle.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>How long do I need to stay on the medication?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Obesity is a chronic condition, and 80&ndash;95% of people regain significant weight after stopping either drug. Most physicians recommend long-term maintenance therapy, potentially at a lower dose. Drug holidays of 4&ndash;8 weeks may restore efficacy if tolerance develops, which happens in about 15&ndash;20% of patients.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Can I combine either drug with other weight loss medications?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Both may be combined with phentermine under medical supervision and are commonly paired with metformin for synergistic effects. However, combining either drug with another GLP-1 agonist is contraindicated. Always discuss combinations with your prescriber.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>What if I can't afford the maintenance dose?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Many patients stay on intermediate doses (semaglutide 1.0 mg, tirzepatide 5&ndash;7.5 mg) and still see good results. Manufacturer savings programs can reduce costs to $25/month for eligible patients with commercial insurance. Compounded versions are cheaper but carry quality and legal risks.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>What are the pregnancy risks?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Discontinue either drug immediately if pregnancy occurs. There is no strong evidence of birth defects, but data is limited. Physicians recommend using contraception while taking either medication and stopping at least 2 months before a planned pregnancy.</div>
  </details>
</div>

<!-- ========== BOTTOM LINE ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Summary</div>
  <p>Tirzepatide's dual agonism produces greater weight loss than semaglutide in every clinical comparison to date. Semaglutide has a longer track record and proven cardiovascular benefits. Cost and access challenges affect both drugs. The "better" choice depends on your individual priorities, response profile, and insurance situation.</p>
</div>

<p>If maximizing weight loss is your primary goal, tirzepatide has the stronger evidence. If you have cardiovascular disease or want the reassurance of a longer safety track record, semaglutide is the more proven option.</p>

<p>Neither drug is a magic bullet. Both work best when paired with resistance training, high-protein nutrition, and consistent medical follow-up. Talk to your doctor about which one fits your specific situation.</p>

